english:
  title: Responding to Poems Left by Various Envoys at Deokryeong Station
  author: Lim Wi-jeong
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Spring arrives in a foreign land, and I remember my homeland.
    At every parting, melancholy stirrings pierce the heart.
    Clouds rise over the northern mountain as rain falls on the south.
    When flowers bloom at the southern house, their fragrance drifts to the north.
    The official lodge sits empty, and spring settles into silence.
    Myth eye sweeps across wild fields where grass stretches without end.
    The nation's grace unpaid before my body grows old with years.
    In this dusty world of red, a graying official's sorrow fills my breast.
  footnotes:
    - This poem is composed as a poetic response to verses left by various envoys at Deokryeong Station, a waystation along an important route. Each line incorporates the name of a renowned poet, creating a sophisticated literary tapestry.
    - The poem expresses the bittersweet emotions of official service—the melancholy of separation, the passage of time, and the unfulfilled desire to repay one's debt to the state, all observed through the changing seasons of spring.
